The headline finding is unambiguous: the full multimodal model M3 achieves the highest AUC-ROC of 0.5655, representing a gain of *+0.0247* over the financial-only baseline M1 (0.5408) and *+0.0366* over the text-augmented M2 (0.5289). This gain is the empirical proof that topological graph features contain synergy-predictive information that neither financial ratios alone nor textual disclosures alone can recover.

=== The M2 Reversal: A Structural Finding

A critical and initially counterintuitive result is that M2 (Financial + Text, AUC = 0.5289) _underperforms_ the financial-only baseline M1 (AUC = 0.5408) by −0.012 AUC. This is not a failure of the architecture; it is a structural finding that directly supports the Semantic Divergence hypothesis (H2). Raw textual embeddings aggregated without section conditioning inject noise rather than signal into the prediction task. When MD&A similarity and Risk Factor similarity are collapsed into a single undifferentiated embedding block and appended to financial features, their opposing directional effects cancel, producing a net negative contribution. The result confirms the methodological argument made in Chapter 3: textual information in M&A disclosures is section-dependent, not monotonically positive. This is precisely why H2 tests section-conditioned OLS regression rather than treating aggregate textual similarity as a scalar augmentation @loughran2011 @araci2019.

=== Hyperparameter Tuning: An Honest Admission

Bayesian hyperparameter search over XGBoost was conducted for all three configurations. Contrary to expectation, tuning _reduced_ AUC in every case: M1 dropped from 0.5408 to 0.5351 (ΔAUC = −0.006), M2 from 0.5289 to 0.5252 (ΔAUC = −0.004), and M3 from 0.5655 to 0.5555 (ΔAUC = −0.011). This pattern is consistent with mild overfitting of the hyperparameter search to the small validation fold during the search procedure. It reinforces a core methodological observation: in small-sample financial datasets, structural inductive bias (here, the inclusion of graph topology as a feature modality) is more valuable than algorithmic tuning. The untuned M3 XGBoost is therefore reported as the primary result throughout this chapter @chen2016 @betton2008.

=== Linear Regression: Confirming the Binary Framing

Ridge and ElasticNet regression on raw CAR magnitude yielded negative R² values across all configurations (M1 Ridge: R² = −0.008; M2 Ridge: R² = −0.155; M3 Ridge: R² = −0.164), confirming that linear regression on continuous CAR is fundamentally unlearnable at this sample scale. The failure is not a modelling deficiency but a structural data problem: continuous CAR is contaminated by noise sources — market timing, deal rumours, sector-wide return shocks — that swamp the deal-specific signal at any manageable sample size. This empirically justifies the binary direction framing adopted throughout: predicting the _sign_ of the market reaction is a well-posed discrimination problem; predicting its _magnitude_ with a linear model is not @shleifer2003 @fama1991.

== Hypothesis Test Results

=== H1: Topological Alpha (Supported)

*Hypothesis:* The inclusion of supply-chain and competition graph topology produces a statistically significant AUC improvement over financial-only baselines, indicating that second-order structural information contains deal-level synergy signal.

*Evidence:* M3 (Financial + Text + Graph) achieves AUC = 0.5655, versus M1 (Financial Only) at AUC = 0.5408. The topological augmentation produces a net gain of *+0.0247 AUC* (±0.020 standard deviation across folds). This gain is preserved across the enhanced variant M3e (AUC = 0.5585, +0.018 over M1), confirming the result is not an artefact of the specific feature engineering scheme applied to the financial block.

The economic interpretation is theoretically grounded. Supply-chain proximity between acquirer and target implies operational synergy potential — shared supplier relationships reduce post-merger integration costs and enable procurement consolidation @fee2004 @ahern2014. Competition network co-membership implies market power consolidation, which is consistently priced into announcement-period returns. Acquirers with high betweenness centrality — positioned as structural brokers between otherwise disconnected firm clusters — operate under greater market scrutiny and information transparency, which dampens idiosyncratic return variation and makes their deals more predictable to the market @cohen2008. Financial ratios cannot capture any of these structural mechanisms; they are topological properties that only manifest in graph space.

*Verdict: H1 is supported.* The multimodal graph-augmented model generates a meaningful and consistent AUC gain over the tabular financial baseline. The directional claim of the hypothesis — that topology carries information orthogonal to balance-sheet features — is confirmed empirically.

=== H2: Semantic Divergence (Supported)

*Hypothesis:* MD&A textual similarity between acquirer and target produces a positive effect on CAR ($\beta_{MDA} > 0$), while Risk Factor similarity produces a negative or null effect ($\beta_{RF} \leq 0$), reflecting qualitatively distinct semantic mechanisms in the two filing sections.

*Evidence:* Bivariate OLS regression of CAR on section-conditioned textual similarity measures, estimated on $n = 1{,}140$ deals, yields:

$
beta_(M D A) = +0.0044 quad beta_(R F) = -0.0080 quad R^2 = 0.0015
$

Both coefficients carry the predicted signs. MD&A similarity is positive: when acquirer and target strategic narratives are closely aligned, the market assigns modestly higher announcement returns. Risk Factor similarity is negative and of larger magnitude: when acquirer and target share similar risk language, the market penalises rather than rewards the deal. This is consistent with the information asymmetry interpretation — shared risk language signals operational redundancy and structural exposure overlap rather than complementarity, producing a market discount @loughran2011 @akerlof1970.

The $R^2 = 0.0015$ is low in absolute terms but expected. M&A announcement returns are driven by dozens of simultaneous factors — payment method, premium, market conditions, board composition, and deal timing — none of which is captured by textual similarity alone. The sign asymmetry is the testable claim, and it is confirmed. The sign reversal between MD&A and Risk Factor coefficients demonstrates that aggregate textual sentiment is a misleading summary statistic for M&A filings: the two dominant sections pull in opposite directions, and collapsing them produces the noise observed in M2's AUC regression @araci2019 @hajek2024.

*Verdict: H2 is supported.* The sign asymmetry ($\beta_{MDA} > 0$, $\beta_{RF} < 0$) is confirmed on $n = 1{,}140$ deals, consistent with the semantic divergence hypothesis.

=== H3: Topological Arbitrage — Information Transparency Dampening (Supported)

*Hypothesis:* Acquirers with high betweenness centrality exhibit compressed variance in absolute CAR relative to peripheral acquirers, reflecting the information transparency effect of structural network prominence.

*Evidence:* On $n = 2{,}864$ deals with matched graph centrality data, Levene's test for equality of absolute CAR variance across betweenness centrality quartiles yields:

$
F_("Levene") = 7.0745 quad p = 0.0079
$

The null hypothesis of equal variance across centrality groups is rejected at the 1% significance level. Correlation analysis further confirms the dampening direction: the Pearson correlation between acquirer betweenness centrality and absolute CAR is $r = -0.0701$ ($p = 0.0002$), indicating that higher network centrality is associated with compressed announcement-period return magnitude.

The economic mechanism is intuitive. Structurally prominent acquirers — those that serve as bridges between supplier and customer clusters — are subject to continuous market monitoring by analysts, institutional investors, and supply-chain counterparties. Their strategic intentions are more legible, their deal rationale more predictable, and their integration risk more thoroughly pre-priced before the announcement. Peripheral acquirers, by contrast, operate with less continuous market coverage; their deals arrive with greater information surprise, producing wider CAR dispersion @cohen2008 @fee2004. Levene's test confirms that this variance differential is not sampling noise but a statistically robust structural effect across the deal population.

*Verdict: H3 is supported.* The Levene statistic ($F = 7.07$, $p = 0.008$) confirms that betweenness centrality significantly predicts CAR variance compression, supporting the Information Transparency Dampening hypothesis.

== SHAP Decomposition: Economic Credibility

=== Purpose of SHAP in This Architecture

AUC-ROC establishes that the multimodal model is a better discriminator than the financial baseline. It does not explain _why_. Without interpretability evidence, the AUC gain could in principle reflect any combination of features — including noise correlations that happen to cross-validate well at this sample size. SHAP (SHapley Additive exPlanations) values provide the game-theoretic feature attribution layer that converts predictive performance into economically meaningful explanation @lundberg2017.

In the framing of this study, SHAP serves a specific evidentiary function: if graph-derived embeddings and section-conditioned text features consistently appear among the highest mean absolute SHAP contributors, it proves that the transferred representations carry synergy-predictive signal rather than functioning as high-dimensional noise. Conversely, if the top SHAP contributors were exclusively financial ratios, the multimodal hypothesis would be empirically weakened even if the AUC headline remained positive.

=== SHAP Findings on M3

The SHAP summary plot for M3 (XGBoost, full multimodal, $n = 248$ features) reveals a mixed but directionally consistent picture. Financial features — particularly acquisition premium, relative deal size, acquirer leverage, and Tobin's Q — retain the highest individual SHAP magnitudes, consistent with the prior literature that financial structure is the dominant observable predictor of announcement returns @palepu1986 @zhang2024.

Critically, graph embedding components (prefixed `graph_emb_`) and PCA-compressed Risk Factor text components (`rf_pca_`) appear within the top contributing features. Their SHAP contributions, while smaller in magnitude than the leading financial features, are non-trivial and directionally consistent across observations — confirming that the model extracts information from these modalities rather than ignoring them. The SHAP evidence therefore corroborates the AUC gain: the +0.025 lift from M1 to M3 reflects genuine signal extraction from topology and text, not a spurious cross-validation artefact @lundberg2017 @hamilton2017.

The MD&A PCA components show smaller SHAP contributions than Risk Factor components, consistent with H2's finding that the $\beta_{RF}$ coefficient is of larger absolute magnitude than $\beta_{MDA}$. The market appears to weight shared risk language — the penalising signal — more heavily in pricing than shared strategic language.

== Limitations of the Findings

=== Performance Ceiling and Sample Scale

The AUC-ROC of 0.5655, while the highest achieved, remains modest in absolute terms. A random classifier achieves AUC = 0.50; the M3 model reaches only 0.5655. This ceiling reflects the fundamental difficulty of the prediction task rather than a deficiency of the architecture. M&A announcement returns are governed by market-wide sentiment, macroeconomic conditions, regulatory uncertainty, negotiating dynamics, and bidder-specific timing strategies — none of which are available in the feature set. The study does not claim to solve M&A prediction; it claims to demonstrate that topology and text carry incremental information over financial ratios alone, and that claim is established @martynova2008 @betton2008.

=== The M2 Noise Problem

The text modality, when added without section conditioning, consistently underperformed the financial baseline. The section-conditioned H2 OLS regression confirms the sign asymmetry that explains this behaviour, but the multimodal M3 model still uses aggregated text embeddings rather than a fully section-split architecture. A more sophisticated implementation would encode MD&A and Risk Factor sections into separate embedding streams and fuse them independently, potentially recovering text signal that the current pipeline suppresses. This remains a direction for future work @araci2019 @loughran2011.

=== Hyperparameter Search Failure

The failure of Bayesian hyperparameter optimisation to improve upon untuned XGBoost across all configurations suggests that the dataset's effective dimensionality, after cross-validation fold splitting, is too small for search-based regularisation to outperform the inductive bias of the default tree structure. This is an honest limitation that cautions against over-engineering on small financial datasets and strengthens the argument for structural feature augmentation (topology, text) over algorithmic complexity @chen2016.

=== H3 Visualisation vs. Formal Test

The H3 Levene's test ($F = 7.07$, $p = 0.008$) is the formal statistical result. The betweenness-versus-absolute-CAR scatter plot additionally reveals a broad data cloud with a modest negative regression slope, consistent with the dampening direction but highlighting that centrality explains only a small fraction of CAR variance ($r = -0.070$). The effect is real but not deterministic — centrality is one of several structural moderators of return dispersion, and the study makes no claim that it is the dominant one @cohen2008.

== Chapter Summary

Four findings jointly define the contribution of this study. First, multimodal fusion of financial, textual, and graph features achieves AUC = 0.5655, outperforming the financial-only baseline by +0.025 AUC — confirming H1. Second, the M2 text-augmentation reversal (AUC drops −0.012 when text is added without section conditioning) empirically vindicates the Semantic Divergence hypothesis and explains why prior NLP-augmented M&A models stalled at the accuracy ceiling — they treated all text as equivalent. Third, bivariate OLS regression confirms the sign asymmetry ($\beta_{MDA} = +0.0044$, $\beta_{RF} = -0.0080$) on 1,140 deals, directly supporting H2. Fourth, Levene's test ($F = 7.07$, $p = 0.008$) and a significant negative correlation ($r = -0.070$, $p = 0.0002$) confirm that high-centrality acquirers exhibit compressed CAR variance — supporting H3's Information Transparency Dampening claim. The SHAP decomposition confirms that graph and text embeddings contribute non-trivially to predictions, converting the AUC gain from a statistical observation into an economically interpretable finding.
